post_cb({"8511518": {"Id": "8511518", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Yes, because you're reading the value of a variable (<code>x</code>) which was uninitialised and unassigned.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2011-12-14T20:55:24.540", "CommentCount": "4", "CreationDate": "2011-12-14T20:55:24.540", "ParentId": "8511478", "Score": "6", "OwnerUserId": "726361"}, "8511478": {"ViewCount": "162", "Body": "<p>Does the following invoke undefined behavior?</p>\n<pre><code>int x;\nint i = x;\n</code></pre>\n<p>Reference from C++03</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_8511478_8511478_0\">(4.1/1) If the object to which the lvalue refers is not an object of type T\n  and is not an object of a type derived from T, or <strong>if the object is\n  uninitialized</strong>, a program that necessitates this conversion has\n  undefined behavior.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Edit:</strong>\nHowever, from (3.3.1/1) an object may be initialized with its own indetermine value, why is that? i.e.</p>\n<pre><code>int x = x; //not an undefined behaviour\n</code></pre>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "8511518", "Title": "Initializing object with indeterminate value", "CreationDate": "2011-12-14T20:52:20.493", "Id": "8511478", "CommentCount": "3", "LastEditDate": "2011-12-14T21:41:13.330", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "963864", "LastActivityDate": "2011-12-14T22:08:59.133", "Score": "2", "OwnerUserId": "1086635", "Tags": "<c++><initialization><undefined-behavior>", "AnswerCount": "5"}, "8511503": {"Id": "8511503", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>It invokes perfectly defined behavior. Whatever garbage value x was when it is allocated on the stack will be assigned to i as is.</p>\n<p>Depending on your compiler, however, you may get a compile time warning about referencing an uninitialized variable.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2011-12-14T20:54:30.757", "CommentCount": "9", "CreationDate": "2011-12-14T20:54:30.757", "ParentId": "8511478", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "1094630"}, "8512069": {"Id": "8512069", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_8511478_8512069_0\">int x = x; //not an undefined behaviour</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Wrong.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2011-12-14T21:41:57.637", "CommentCount": "2", "CreationDate": "2011-12-14T21:41:57.637", "ParentId": "8511478", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "963864"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_8511478_8511478_0": {"length": 8, "quality": 0.5333333333333333, "section_id": 7192}}, "n3337": {"so_8511478_8511478_0": {"length": 13, "quality": 0.8666666666666667, "section_id": 5}}, "n4659": {"so_8511478_8511478_0": {"length": 8, "quality": 0.5333333333333333, "section_id": 8701}}}, "8511625": {"Id": "8511625", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>The only thing to remember is that this is okay:</p>\n<pre><code>static int x;\nint j = x;\n</code></pre>\n<p>but your example is not.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2011-12-14T21:04:29.353", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2011-12-14T21:04:29.353", "ParentId": "8511478", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "906773"}, "8511593": {"Id": "8511593", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>It's undefined if <code>x</code> is uninitialized, as said in your quote.</p>\n<pre><code>int x; // 0 initialized\nint i = x;\n\nint main() {\n  int z; // not initialized\n  int k = z; // UB\n}\n</code></pre>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "964135", "LastActivityDate": "2011-12-14T22:08:59.133", "Score": "0", "CreationDate": "2011-12-14T21:01:28.427", "ParentId": "8511478", "CommentCount": "1", "OwnerUserId": "964135", "LastEditDate": "2011-12-14T22:08:59.133"}});